{ Harassing the Bishop which usually retreats to h7 and gambits the h-pawn. However, other tries are not immediately losing. }
8... Bh7
{ The most common reaction and where most of preparation should be spent. Doubled g-pawns are very easy to target by White if Black allows such a situation. }
9. Nxh5 { White should accept the offered pawn on h5. } 9... Nc6 10. dxc5
{ Time to capture on c5 as defense of the e-pawn is difficult if we allow cxd4. }
10... Bxc5 { Correctly capturing the c-pawn and developing the Bishop. } 11.
Bb5
{ It is best to not give up the e-pawn too easily. In general, White is going to take the Knight on c6 if Black plays the most common Qc7 or d4 as speed of development is the most important factor and we need to see how Black recaptures given the vulnerable e-pawn. }
11... Qc7
{ This is by far the most common move for Black, and it scores well for them, but not if White knows how to fight. }
12. Bxc6+ { The Knight on c6 has to go in order to stabilize the e-pawn. }
12... Qxc6
{ Capturing with the Queen is the correct decision when d4 is threatened. Capturing with the b-pawn works out well for White after Nxg7+. }
13. Qf3
{ The Queen goes to the thematic square f3. The importance of the Queen being on f3 is that from f3 the Queen provides tactical possibilities based on Nxg7 Kf8 and Nxe6 when the f-pawn is pinned. It also allows for an exchange of Queens if/when Black plays an eventual d4. }
13... Kf8 { Guarding the g-pawn is the best defense. } 14. Bg5
{ Developing to the most aggressive square has been the preferred historical path, but Rh3 is an interesting alternative. }
14... Rc8
{ Pressuring the c-file for counter-play. Never played, but possibly better is Bd4 though White is still fine. }
15. O-O
{ Rh3 is a viable alternative, but connecting the Rooks and preparing to place one on d1 is quite sensible. }
15... d4
{ Black sees an opportunity to take the Queens off and seizes on it which alleviates a lot of the pressure on their King. }
16. Qxc6 { Trading is forced. } 16... Rxc6
{ The most testing capture. Capturing with the b-pawn is possible, but leaves Black with a very passive position. }
17. Rad1
{ We are pretty far down the theory path, but this is a critical moment that White needs to know what to do and it is a tad unintuitive. This is the only move that keeps White from handing the advantage over to Black. Naturally it stops dxc3, but Bxc2 looks problematic. Nonetheless, this is the correct path forward. }
17... Nh6
{ Tempting, but the Knight is really needed on e7 to disrupt communication between the Bishop and a Rook on d8. Black is worse versus the main line as we will show with similar play. }
18. Na4 { As played in the main line. } 18... Be7
{ Putting a different piece on e7 is Black's intention. } 19. Rxd4 Bxc2 20. Rd7
Bxa4 21. Bxe7+ Ke8 22. Rxb7
{ White's aggressive position is sufficient for a decisive position. For example, Nxg7 is threatening mate and b3 is threatening to win the Bishop. Therefore, Black's best try is   22...Nf5  , but White calmly plays  23.Bg5  and now White either has  Rb8+  winning the Rook or  b3  winning the Bishop or Rook takes  a7  with a winning position. }
*

