[White "2. Main Line 6. ... c5 Systems"]
[Black "c5 with h5 Variation #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... c5
{ This is generally considered the strongest defense and the most commonly played at the GM level. I will cover most of the alternative attempts, but if you have limited time to spend this is where most of your study should be spent. As mentioned before, the purpose of c5 is to react in the center to the flank attack. It is a bit dogmatic to only play c5 for that purpose, but suffice it to say that trying to break up White's pawn center and to provide some counter-play is the most classical attempt to play as Black. f6 and h6 are the next most common lines, though f6 and Ne7 are the most common alternatives to c5 at the GM level. I will have less to say about alternative moves beyond those, but will mention a general plan for them if they have been played a significant number of times. }
7. h4
{ Continuing with our aggression on the kingside with the immediate threat of h5 winning the Bishop. Three major defenses are available here and will be discussed in great detail: h5, h6, and cxd4  (in order of popularity)  . We will briefly consider two other rare defensive attempts: f6 and Nc6. }
7... h5
{ h5 is generally considered the strongest defensive attempt, but it involves the sacrifice of the h-pawn, but when your pieces are cramped, opening the h-file for the Rook to use one day provides some compensation. This can be argued as an example of the first major opportunity to Black to not play optimally. Many players will choose h6 if they are unfamiliar, but h6 gives White a nice game and leaves Black quite passive. }
8. Nf4
{ Harassing the Bishop which usually retreats to h7 and gambits the h-pawn. However, other tries are not immediately losing. }
8... Bh7
{ The most common reaction and where most of preparation should be spent. Doubled g-pawns are very easy to target by White if Black allows such a situation. }
9. Nxh5 { White should accept the offered pawn on h5. } 9... cxd4
{ Slightly more popular than Nc6, but roughly equal in strength. There is more theory to cover with Nc6, so we will make Nc6 our main line for coverage. }
10. Nb5 { White saves the Knight and prepares to retake the pawn on d4. } 10...
Nc6 { Developing and threatening the e-pawn. } 11. Nxd4
{ Taking the d-pawn back. } 11... Nxe5
{ Black gets the pawn back, but ends up with a very congested kingside that is difficult to untangle and has many opportunities to go wrong. }
12. Bb5+
{ This forces Black to retreat to d7 which keeps Black from retreating the Knight to the more natural c6 square. }
12... Nd7 { Forced to prevent significant material loss. } 13. Bg5
{ Qe2 can be played first, but seems to give Black more options though they probably should just transpose. White's intention is to castle long and look to attack the Black King or break up the Black center pawns before Black can get developed. }
13... Ne7 { Developing a piece is the most natural way to defend. } 14. Qe2
{ This prepares to castle long and prevents e5 thus allowing us to maintain our centralized Knight for now. Indeed, Nxe6 is currently a bit of a threat when Black will be unable to castle and White's Rook will come bearing down on the center files rapidly. }
14... a6
{ Black has to relieve some of the pressure so they try to trade a set of pieces. }
15. Bxd7+ { An unavoidable concession if White is to retain any advantage. }
15... Qxd7 { Forced. } 16. O-O-O
{ There are other tries, but castling now continues to maintain the pressure on Black and gives them the most opportunities to go astray. }
16... O-O-O
{ Most other moves can be met with Rhe1 with a significant advantage. Black has the center pawns as compensation for the poor piece activity, but they are not particularly mobile without creating significant risk to their airy King. }
17. Rh3
{ The most aggressive option which leaves Black only one move that does not lose immediately, Kb8. b5 is met with Rf3 and f6 is fatal after Nxf6. After Kb8, White has a natural attack brewing with Rc3, Qe5, and Bf4. Black can likely hold, but White's position is much easier to play. }
*

