[Black "c5 with h5 Variation #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... c5
{ This is generally considered the strongest defense and the most commonly played at the GM level. I will cover most of the alternative attempts, but if you have limited time to spend this is where most of your study should be spent. As mentioned before, the purpose of c5 is to react in the center to the flank attack. It is a bit dogmatic to only play c5 for that purpose, but suffice it to say that trying to break up White's pawn center and to provide some counter-play is the most classical attempt to play as Black. f6 and h6 are the next most common lines, though f6 and Ne7 are the most common alternatives to c5 at the GM level. I will have less to say about alternative moves beyond those, but will mention a general plan for them if they have been played a significant number of times. }
7. h4
{ Continuing with our aggression on the kingside with the immediate threat of h5 winning the Bishop. Three major defenses are available here and will be discussed in great detail: h5, h6, and cxd4  (in order of popularity)  . We will briefly consider two other rare defensive attempts: f6 and Nc6. }
7... h5
{ h5 is generally considered the strongest defensive attempt, but it involves the sacrifice of the h-pawn, but when your pieces are cramped, opening the h-file for the Rook to use one day provides some compensation. This can be argued as an example of the first major opportunity to Black to not play optimally. Many players will choose h6 if they are unfamiliar, but h6 gives White a nice game and leaves Black quite passive. }
8. Nf4
{ Harassing the Bishop which usually retreats to h7 and gambits the h-pawn. However, other tries are not immediately losing. }
8... cxd4
{ Often tried, but giving up the light-squared Bishop is positionally questionable. }
9. Nxg6
{ Just as in 8... Nc6, if Black lets you take the light-square Bishop with the Knight and has to recapture with the f-pawn, it is usually the correct path forward with natural moves to attack the doubled g-pawns. }
9... fxg6 { Forced. } 10. Qxd4
{ Nb5 scores quite well, but I am unconvinced after Black plays Bc5 and suspect Black may actually be better after trading on d4. }
10... Nc6 { Developing with an attack on the Queen. } 11. Bb5
{ Developing with a pin to protect the Queen. } 11... Ne7
{ Developing the Knight is the strongest move, but the Knight now blocks the Bishop in and Black is still prevented from castling. }
12. Bg5 { Developing the last minor and now both Knights are pinned. } 12...
Qc7
{ This move tries to allow castling long and a subsequent threat to the e-pawn. }
13. O-O-O
{ f4 is a bit too slow for the position when hxg gives Black some advantage. The line I recommend is O-O-O, which has not scored well in the past, but I have an improvement involving a piece sacrifice that I think turns the assessment in White's favor. For those seeking to look in other more conservative directions, both Qa5 and gxh are options, but I find Black to be equal in both. }
13... a6
{ The most natural attempt to break the pin and ease Black's position. } 14.
Bxc6+
{ My database only has Bxe7 here. I find this completely against the spirit of the opening to allow Black's Bishop to get free so easily. }
14... Nxc6
{ White gets a freehand with any other capture as the Knight remains blocking the Bishop in on f8. }
15. Nxd5
{ A fascinating piece sacrifice which I believe keeps the advantage in White's hands. For the sacrifice, White gets both center pawns, the Black King remains in the center under fire, White retains a very dangerous center pawn, and the Rook on h8 remains unemployed for a good while yet. This is more than enough compensation in my opinion. Know this move as O-O-O is not likely to produce any advantage without this sacrifice. Qd3 is the serious alternative for an even position. }
15... exd5 { The piece must be accepted. } 16. Qxd5
{ Getting our second pawn and threatening to get a third with Qe6+ and Qxg6. }
16... Be7
{ Likely the best defense which threatens to play Rd8 or Bxg5 and release the Rook from h8. }
17. Qe6
{ The g-pawn can no longer be saved without giving the piece back with Qxe5. If   17...Qxe5  , then  18.Qxe5  Nxe5  19.Bxe7  Kxe7  20.Rhe1  Ke6  21.f4  picks the piece back up with a roughly equal position. If   17...Rd8  , then  18.gxh5  gxh5  19.f4  leaves White with an advantage due to the completely out of play Rook on  h8  and the advanced e-pawn. An example line of play would be:  19...Kf8  20.Rxd8+  Qxd8  21.Rd1  Qe8  22.Qb3  b5  23.e6  Bxg5  24.fxg5  Kg8  25.Rd6  Ne7  26.Qd3  Qg6  27.Rd8+  Kh7  Rxh8+  Kxh8  29.Qd8+  Ng8  30  e7  . }
