1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... c5
{ This is generally considered the strongest defense and the most commonly played at the GM level. I will cover most of the alternative attempts, but if you have limited time to spend this is where most of your study should be spent. As mentioned before, the purpose of c5 is to react in the center to the flank attack. It is a bit dogmatic to only play c5 for that purpose, but suffice it to say that trying to break up White's pawn center and to provide some counter-play is the most classical attempt to play as Black. f6 and h6 are the next most common lines, though f6 and Ne7 are the most common alternatives to c5 at the GM level. I will have less to say about alternative moves beyond those, but will mention a general plan for them if they have been played a significant number of times. }
7. h4
{ Continuing with our aggression on the kingside with the immediate threat of h5 winning the Bishop. Three major defenses are available here and will be discussed in great detail: h5, h6, and cxd4  (in order of popularity)  . We will briefly consider two other rare defensive attempts: f6 and Nc6. }
7... h5
{ h5 is generally considered the strongest defensive attempt, but it involves the sacrifice of the h-pawn, but when your pieces are cramped, opening the h-file for the Rook to use one day provides some compensation. This can be argued as an example of the first major opportunity to Black to not play optimally. Many players will choose h6 if they are unfamiliar, but h6 gives White a nice game and leaves Black quite passive. }
8. Nf4
{ Harassing the Bishop which usually retreats to h7 and gambits the h-pawn. However, other tries are not immediately losing. }
8... Ne7
{ A common mistake. Black tries to defend the Bishop with the Knight. Fortunately for us, that weakens a very important square. }
9. Nb5
{ Nge7 blocked the defense of the d6 square. Allowing Nd6+ without the ability to capture it is very problematic for Black. }
9... Nec6
{ The only reasonable try for Black, but now the Bishop on g6 can be captured with a doubling of the g-pawns. }
10. Nxg6 { Taking advantage of Black's error. } 10... fxg6 { Forced. } 11. Qd3
{ This is sufficient for an advantage, but Bg5 is likely even stronger. Bg5 requires knowing the sharp lines following Qa5 12. b4! which may be asking too much for such a rather obscure line. After the recommended 12. Qd3, Black has to find   12...Kd7  which is very unintuitive and White retains an advantage even if they do find it with  13.c3  and seeking to compete development with  Bg5  or  Be3  before targeting the weaknesses in Black's position and opening the center for an attack on the King. Feel free to take your own path here, either move is endorsed. Note,  12...Kf7 ?  loses spectacularly to  13.gxh5 !  Rxh5  14.Bh3  cxd4  15.Bxe6+  followed by  Qxg6  hitting the loose Rook on  h5.  This is a great tactic to be aware of in lines where Black tries to stubbornly defend the  g6  pawn. }
