1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... c5
{ This is generally considered the strongest defense and the most commonly played at the GM level. I will cover most of the alternative attempts, but if you have limited time to spend this is where most of your study should be spent. As mentioned before, the purpose of c5 is to react in the center to the flank attack. It is a bit dogmatic to only play c5 for that purpose, but suffice it to say that trying to break up White's pawn center and to provide some counter-play is the most classical attempt to play as Black. f6 and h6 are the next most common lines, though f6 and Ne7 are the most common alternatives to c5 at the GM level. I will have less to say about alternative moves beyond those, but will mention a general plan for them if they have been played a significant number of times. }
7. h4
{ Continuing with our aggression on the kingside with the immediate threat of h5 winning the Bishop. Three major defenses are available here and will be discussed in great detail: h5, h6, and cxd4  (in order of popularity)  . We will briefly consider two other rare defensive attempts: f6 and Nc6. }
7... Nc6
{ Not particularly common, but has been played enough times to mention. } 8. h5
{ Taking the minor exchange is clearly the best response. } 8... Bxc2
{ Not as bad as it would appear at first, though inadequate and rarely played. All you need to know is that it is safe to take the piece and after cxd4 either Nd1, a novelty, or Nb1 are adequate to have an advantage, but Black has some compensation, just not enough, for the piece. }
9. Qxc2 { Again, taking the piece is perfectly fine. } 9... cxd4
{ Black takes as much material and strives to inconvenience White's pieces as much as possible for the sacrificed piece. }
10. Nd1
{ Nb1 is traditionally played, but Nd1 looks even stronger. White's plan here is to hang onto the piece and untangle with Bd2, Bg2, and Rc1 when slowly the extra Black pawns will not be worth the piece in a middlegame. }
