7. h4
{ Continuing with our aggression on the kingside with the immediate threat of h5 winning the Bishop. Three major defenses are available here and will be discussed in great detail: h5, h6, and cxd4  (in order of popularity)  . We will briefly consider two other rare defensive attempts: f6 and Nc6. }
7... f6
{ A logical attempt to further break up the White pawn center. The debate will argue around whether the e-pawn is too weak now for Black's level of development. }
8. exf6 { Opening lines of attack appears to be White's most promising path. }
8... Nxf6
{ Developing is the most principled capture. gxf6 has been tried equally often, but looks a little loose and it is a heavy load on the dark-square Bishop to defend the c-pawn and the dark-square complex on the kingside. So, I recommend dxc5 immediately, followed by Nf4, if Black plays gxf6. White's pieces will find natural squares and a comfortable attack developing. }
9. Bh3
{ Immediately creating pressure on the weakened e-pawn. g5 first is not as strong as, after Nh5, White's continuations with Nf4 are mitigated since Black can play Nxf4. }
9... h6
{ White looks to play g5 to increase the pressure from the Bishop on h3. h6 strives to limit the strength of g5 by opening a line for the Rook on h8 with hxg5. }
10. Nf4
{ White begins to pressure the weakness at e6. The general plan will be to play Qe2 and g5 to add maximum pressure to the e-pawn. If Black takes on d4, then Nb5 will provide recapture with yet another piece pressuring e6. }
