{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... c5
{ This is generally considered the strongest defense and the most commonly played at the GM level. I will cover most of the alternative attempts, but if you have limited time to spend this is where most of your study should be spent. As mentioned before, the purpose of c5 is to react in the center to the flank attack. It is a bit dogmatic to only play c5 for that purpose, but suffice it to say that trying to break up White's pawn center and to provide some counter-play is the most classical attempt to play as Black. f6 and h6 are the next most common lines, though f6 and Ne7 are the most common alternatives to c5 at the GM level. I will have less to say about alternative moves beyond those, but will mention a general plan for them if they have been played a significant number of times. }
7. h4
{ Continuing with our aggression on the kingside with the immediate threat of h5 winning the Bishop. Three major defenses are available here and will be discussed in great detail: h5, h6, and cxd4  (in order of popularity)  . We will briefly consider two other rare defensive attempts: f6 and Nc6. }
7... cxd4
{ The third most popular defense at this point. Play takes on a much different flavor in this line versus the h5 and h6 defenses. This is mostly due to the need to recapture with the Knight which takes all the ideas with Nf4 away. On the plus side, this centralizes the Knight and gives White a new, arguably better, option of launching the f-pawn up the board. Play gets quite tactical in these lines, so hold on tight ! }
8. Nxd4
{ Capturing with the Knight so that if the Knight comes to c6, Bb5 will have two pieces immediately threatening capture on c6. }
8... h5 { Dealing with the threatened Bishop on g6. } 9. Bb5+
{ Developing in such a way that the Knight is compelled to the inferior d7-square instead of the c6-square. }
9... Nd7 { Essentially forced as Ke7 cannot be worth consideration. } 10. f4
{ Time to open the center. } 10... hxg4
{ Black seeks counter-play on the h-file. } 11. f5
{ Flank threats are met with center play. Who cares about an h-pawn when the King is on the menu!? }
11... Rxh4
{ Taking the pawn and creating a passed pawn that could be a problem if given time. }
12. Rf1 { A key move which adds more power to the attack on White's King. }
12... exf5
{ This is the best try, but it is inadequate. With best play, White has a decisive attack already. }
13. e6
{ A thematic push that gives White a phenomenal position against the Black King. }
13... fxe6 { Nothing else is better as White will capture on d7 decisively. }
14. Qe2
{ It is much stronger to capture on e6 with the Queen if we can manage to do so without having to trade them. }
14... Qe7 { This is the most logical attempt. } 15. Bg5
{ Deflecting the Queen is a decisive blow to the Black defenses. } 15... Qxg5
{ Obviously, Nf6 or moving the Queen fails to Bxh4. } 16. Bxd7+
{ Qxe6 may also be winning, but Bxd7 is more forcing and preferable to me. }
16... Kxd7 { Forced. } 17. Qxe6+
{ Capturing with check is the way to convert. } 17... Kd8
{ The only try as Kc7 allows the other Knight to join in the fight. } 18. Qxd5+
{ White is winning as neither   18...Kc8  19.Qe6+  nor   18...Ke8  19.Qb5+  (the best tries for Black)  work. }
*

