[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... c5
{ This is generally considered the strongest defense and the most commonly played at the GM level. I will cover most of the alternative attempts, but if you have limited time to spend this is where most of your study should be spent. As mentioned before, the purpose of c5 is to react in the center to the flank attack. It is a bit dogmatic to only play c5 for that purpose, but suffice it to say that trying to break up White's pawn center and to provide some counter-play is the most classical attempt to play as Black. f6 and h6 are the next most common lines, though f6 and Ne7 are the most common alternatives to c5 at the GM level. I will have less to say about alternative moves beyond those, but will mention a general plan for them if they have been played a significant number of times. }
7. h4
{ Continuing with our aggression on the kingside with the immediate threat of h5 winning the Bishop. Three major defenses are available here and will be discussed in great detail: h5, h6, and cxd4  (in order of popularity)  . We will briefly consider two other rare defensive attempts: f6 and Nc6. }
7... h6
{ The second most popular try, but this attempt is quite passive and does not afford Black as much counter-play since the Rook on h8 remains uninvolved. }
8. Be3
{ Developing and threatening to capture the c-pawn which compels a response from Black. }
8... Nc6
{ This the most common try for Black which recognizes the need to develop. } 9.
dxc5
{ White gives up the center to have open lines. This is the best move, but there are critical tactics to know. }
9... Nxe5
{ By far the most common move, but there are rare alternatives for which you may want to be prepared. In particular, a6 is a source of alternative play by Black to keep the Bishop from arriving on b5. I could find only one game in my database of this being played, but be prepared for it. If a6 is played, f4 is the most natural next move. }
10. Nf4 { Designed to let the Bishop get to b5 with tempo and pressure d5. }
10... Bh7
{ Retaining the Bishop is the most natural move since Black would rather not trade off either of their two best pieces at the moment. Although, a6 is interesting yet again. }
11. Bb5+ { Developing the last minor piece and tying down Black's pieces. }
11... Nc6 { Better than the more passive Nd7. } 12. Qe2
{ Creating tactical threats involving Nxd5 and preparing to castle long to bring a Rook to the d-file which creates even more threats. }
12... Ne7
{ Black really needs to hurry now or sacrifices will finish them off. This blocks the Queen checks and helps defend the d5 pawn, but at the price of leaving the Bishop locked in. }
13. O-O-O { This secures the White King and adds the Rook to the attack. }
13... Qa5
{ Getting one of royal family out of the line of fire and perhaps allowing the Black King to escape by castling long. }
14. Bd2
{ Likely the only move to keep the pressure on Black as allowing them to castle is dubious. }
14... d4
{ This is the most dangerous move, but White has an excellent answer. } 15. a3
{ Now taking the piece prevents Black castling as castling immediately loses the exchange to Ne4 and Nd6  (not Ncd5 as d3 allows the Queen to escape)  . }
*

