[Round "?"]
[White "3. 6. ... f6 Systems"]
[Black "f6 with fxe5 Variation #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... f6
{ Black plays to undermine the White center. Again, the most popular line is to play c5 to undermine the center from the other side. This is the second most common move, but will often become a transposition to c5 or Nd7 the next move. I will also look at the most likely independent move, fxe5, in some detail. }
7. h4
{ h4 provides us a lot of transpositions to other lines that are favorable which keeps our preparation load to a minimum. Not to mention, continuing forward with threatening the Bishop and gaining space is likely the best move. Nf4 is more popular, but scores worse. Feel free to consider it instead if you like. }
7... fxe5
{ This is the only notable continuation of independent value. Other worthy moves are transpositions and covered in their alternative move orders. With fxe5, Black immediately begins to break down the White center, but their lag in development makes this a bit risky at the moment. }
8. h5
{ Gaining more space with tempo by hitting the Bishop which should respond by reducing its influence with a retreat to f7. }
8... Bf7
{ The best response for Black. exd is answered by hxg6 when Rxh7 is winning if Black takes the piece on c3 and otherwise they is just down a piece for no compensation. Be4 is met by the usual Nxe4  (a standard response when a legal move)  and White is already considerably better. }
9. dxe5
{ Retaking the pawn. The e-pawn is a bit of a thorn in Black's position as it effectively hinders the King's Knight from going to f6 and locks the light-square Bishop behind its own pawns. Even the dark-square Bishop is impacted as both it and the Knight would like use of the e7 square. }
9... Nd7
{ Nd7 is the most common move at this point. This prepares possibly castling queenside, and secures the Bishop to come to c5 if desired, but does little to else to provide Black with adequate counter-play. c5, allowing the Knight to come to c6, looks more natural but has been played much less often. }
10. f4
{ Invariably played. The f-pawn bolsters the e-pawn long enough to let White develop further and then can be an effective lever to open the position with a timely f5. }
10... Bc5
{ This is the other try Black has made in the position. It is understandable that Black wants to develop this Bishop somewhere active, but the reality is that the Bishop just gets in the way of Black's superior strategic plan which should involve a c5 push. }
11. Nd4
{ This move is designed to release the Bishop and reroute the Knight to b3 or f3 in some lines when White's pieces are all enjoying more freedom. Qd3 is a very interesting alternative which seeks to allow the Queen to get out of the way before playing Bd2. Nd4 seems more natural and gives White a good game. }
11... Qb6 { Aggressive placement while also allowing castling. } 12. Nce2
{ With the Queen on b6, other moves are less encouraging. With this move, White prepares to play c3 with a nice position. }
12... O-O-O
{ The logical continuation though White will generally play c3 against most other moves. }
13. c3
{ White has more space, better pawn break options, and far more promising pieces. Therefore, I will conclude at this point with the assessment that White is preferred. Plans may vary depending on Black's play, but typically White will play for b4, Be3, and a general opening of the queenside to attack the Black King. The Bishop can either sit at f1 influencing the queenside or develop to h3 for a central influence. The Rook may go to h2 with anticipation of swinging to the center or queenside as desired. White might castle long, but often will stay in the center or walk to the kingside as needed. }
