{ Black plays to undermine the White center. Again, the most popular line is to play c5 to undermine the center from the other side. This is the second most common move, but will often become a transposition to c5 or Nd7 the next move. I will also look at the most likely independent move, fxe5, in some detail. }
7. h4
{ h4 provides us a lot of transpositions to other lines that are favorable which keeps our preparation load to a minimum. Not to mention, continuing forward with threatening the Bishop and gaining space is likely the best move. Nf4 is more popular, but scores worse. Feel free to consider it instead if you like. }
7... fxe5
{ This is the only notable continuation of independent value. Other worthy moves are transpositions and covered in their alternative move orders. With fxe5, Black immediately begins to break down the White center, but their lag in development makes this a bit risky at the moment. }
8. h5
{ Gaining more space with tempo by hitting the Bishop which should respond by reducing its influence with a retreat to f7. }
8... Bf7
{ The best response for Black. exd is answered by hxg6 when Rxh7 is winning if Black takes the piece on c3 and otherwise they is just down a piece for no compensation. Be4 is met by the usual Nxe4  (a standard response when a legal move)  and White is already considerably better. }
9. dxe5
{ Retaking the pawn. The e-pawn is a bit of a thorn in Black's position as it effectively hinders the King's Knight from going to f6 and locks the light-square Bishop behind its own pawns. Even the dark-square Bishop is impacted as both it and the Knight would like use of the e7 square. }
9... c5
{ This may be stronger for Black as it allows the Knight to develop to the better square c6. c5 has rarely been played at this point so I will only give a brief coverage and recommended plan. }
10. f4
{ f4 needs to be played for the e-pawn, may as well play it now and see to which square the Knight goes. }
10... Nc6 { The point of this move order. } 11. Bd2
{ At this point, I recommend White play this move to begin preparing the option to castle long. The set-up will normally involve playing Ng3, Qf3, Bg2 and considering castling in either direction depending on what Black has done. White has space, options for castling, and a natural break of f5 or g5 or b3-c4 depending on how Black has arranged their pieces. White's pieces develop easily and Black's can develop, but not in a coordinated manner. With so many options available to White, I find the White position to be preferable although this is one of several positions where engines disagree considerably  (presumably due to their inadequacy in evaluating development issues of the kingside pieces)  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
