1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... h6
{ Most of the time this move will transpose to other lines, but there are some instances where the move order favors a different response. }
7. h4
{ Nf4 is most favorable when it either wins the h-pawn or forces the exchange for the Bishop. Therefore, I am recommending h4 instead which allows a lot of transpositions to other lines and reduces our need for preparation. }
7... Be7
{ Instead, c5 allows us to transpose to 6... c5 7. Be3 h6 8. h4 lines, Nd7 allows us to transpose to 6... Nd7 7. h4 h6 8. Be3 lines, and Bb4 allows us to transpose to 6... Bb4 7. h4 h6 8. h5 lines. Other transpositions are possible with the much rarer sidelines that are even less likely to be seen entered through this move order. I will cover only the lines where I think this move order provides an opportunity for a stronger response, or where h4 was not recommendation in the sideline without h6 played first. }
8. Nf4
{ A unique tactical opportunity is available with this move order. It begins with Nf4 ! }
8... Bh7 { Obviously, letting White play Nxg6 concedes White a great game. } 9.
g5 { White intends to force the issue of weakening the light-squares. } 9...
hxg5 { It is critical to refute this obvious move. } 10. hxg5
{ The following combinations exemplify very important patterns when Black plays poorly. }
10... Bxg5 { The obvious capture fails quickly, but nothing else is better. }
11. Nxe6 { The piece on g5 will be lost. } 11... fxe6
{ Nothing else is better. } 12. Qh5+
{ White will pick up the piece on g5 with a decisive advantage. } *

