exf5 { Forced. } 19. Bxe4
{ The pawns are now too dangerous, it is time to sacrifice a piece to destabilize them. }
19... fxe4
{ The most obvious and best move though Qxd6 is enough to keep Black fighting, albeit at a disadvantage. }
20. Bxg5
{ This startling move is the key to the whole line. White exhibits an understanding that superior development is more important than material. }
20... Rxf1+
{ Black tries to limit the exposure to attack by taking a set of Rooks off and preventing White from easily placing their Queen on the critical g4 square. After hxg5 immediately, Qg4 is completely winning. }
21. Qxf1 { Forced. } 21... hxg5
{ This position has occurred no less than eight times in grandmaster play with all of them resulting in a draw. The piece capture is inferior in my opinion, but White needs to know how to proceed as this position is likely too difficult to find the winning chances over the board. Black may indeed have a defense that holds in the subsequent lines, but neither I, nor the engines, can seem to find it. }
22. Qf5
{ Threatening the e and g-pawns. The key to this position is knowing that White needs to take the g-pawn with the Knight when their Queen is on g4 and Black's Queen on f8 so that White gets a powerful discovery when the Knight moves or if the Queen blocks at g7 White gets Qe6+ when the Queen cannot block on f7. Black cannot stop this, but I will give the best attempt. }
22... Qd7
{ Black really wants to trade some material off when the extra piece would be decisive. }
23. Qg6+
{ Not Qxg5 ? which allows Black to trade the Queens off with Qg7 for a winning position. Qxe4 is enough to bail out for a draw if you want as Qxh3 gives up a perpetual since the Black King cannot step to the f-file when the Rook comes as enough reinforcement to mate Black. }
23... Qg7 24. Qe8+ Qf8 25. Qe6+ Qf7 26. Qc8+
{ We need the Queen on f8 so that it is not defending the e6 square which prevents Ne5 when we play Qg4. Furthermore, it allows a timely arrival of the Rook to f1 in some lines. }
26... Qf8 27. Qg4 { Now we get our Queen to g4. } 27... Ne5
{ Attempting to bring a defender closer to the King. } 28. Qe6+
{ Highlighting the value of maneuvering the Black Queen to the f8 square as the only way to save the Knight is to block and self-pin itself. }
28... Nf7 { Otherwise losing the Knight. } 29. Rf1
{ Locking down the pin on the Knight in two directions. Now, Nxg5 will win material. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. 6. ... Ne7 Systems"]
[Black "Ne7 with c5 Variation #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Ne7
{ The Knight does not have a great future here if White does not take on g6 as it blocks in the Bishop. This is a fairly common reaction to Nge2 which clearly threatened to go to f4 hitting the Bishop. }
7. Nf4 { h4 first is met effectively with h5. } 7... c5
{ The standard method for Black to seek counter-play. } 8. h4
{ Creating an immediate threat to the Bishop on g6. } 8... cxd4
{ The only way forward. Note, we have a good reason to play Nf4 earlier in this position. That being that when c5 is played the Knight on e7 is preventing the need to recapture on g6 with a pawn. Hence, the Knight on e7 cannot move which interrupts the Bishop on f8 from defending the d6 square. Therefore, if Black plays h6 here, White has the very strong Nb5, when Nec6 is essentially forced, and then takes the Bishop on g6 getting the weak doubled g-pawns that spell disaster for Black's long-term position. By taking on d4 first, Black creates a need for recapturing that takes White some time to make happen and forces the Knight to leave c3 which grants Black's Bishop the e4 square after h5. }
9. Nb5
{ The correct reaction which prepares to recapture the d-pawn with the Knight. }
9... Nec6
{ The best continuation which frees Blacks dark-square Bishop. Note that Nxg6 now would be ok for Black who can recapture with the h-pawn and granting the Rook some activity. }
10. h5
{ Trying to hunt down the Bishop is the only way for White to get something from the position. }
10... Be4
{ Bxc2 is an interesting alternative, but White achieves more of an advantage by taking the piece. }
11. f3
{ The obvious and best choice. An absolutely fascinating sequence is about to occur with a lot of surprise moves from both sides. This is the longest theory we will cover in the opening, but understanding how to handle this Ne7 line fully is critical to being able to play the Shirov Attack with confidence. The moves are often so unintuitive and necessary, for both sides, that failing to cover them would be too negligent for anyone recommending this opening. So, hold on tight and bear with the lengthy lines. }
11... a6 { The only serious try that has any merit. } 12. Nd6+
{ fxe4 !? and Black is let off the hook with an equal and dangerous position. Instead, Nd6 ! leads to a wild sequence that provides an advantage that has not scored well, but I will show you the correct path along with an option to bail out for a draw if you feel the need. }
12... Bxd6 { Forced. } 13. exd6 { fxe4 here would lose to Bb4. } 13... g5
{ The only way for Black to survive. } 14. Nh3
{ Saving the piece for now and threatening the g-pawn and the Bishop. } 14...
h6
{ This is the strongest response from Black, but Qxd6 is almost enough for equality. }
15. fxe4
{ Taking the piece is very dangerous, but the only way to fight for the win at this point. }
15... dxe4
{ The hanging pawns are very dangerous, but I assure you White is ok here, but clearly this is a sharp line you need to know well. }
16. Bg2
{ It is imperative that White get the King out of the center. White will eventually have to sacrifice a piece to stop the pawns advancing and they need to be better developed when it happens. }
16... f5
{ Black is creating a real avalanche of pawns. This line takes nerves of steel to play. The immediate e3 hands White a significant advantage after either O-O followed by c3 or c3 immediately. }
17. O-O
{ Order is not important here. White can castle then take on f5 or they can take on f5 first. Castling first seems to give Black a bigger chance to go wrong as only castling themself gives Black the appropriate fighting chances. }
17... O-O
{ All other moves lose for Black ! Castling is not particularly a difficult move to find, but it is comforting to know you are winning if they do not do so. I leave it to you to study how to defeat any other tries in this position. }
18. gxf5
{ c3 is to be considered here, but the most forcing line suffices here. } 18...
exf5 { Forced. } 19. Bxe4
{ The pawns are now too dangerous, it is time to sacrifice a piece to destabilize them. }
19... fxe4
{ The most obvious and best move though Qxd6 is enough to keep Black fighting, albeit at a disadvantage. }
20. Bxg5
{ This startling move is the key to the whole line. White exhibits an understanding that superior development is more important than material. }
20... Rxf1+
{ Black tries to limit the exposure to attack by taking a set of Rooks off and preventing White from easily placing their Queen on the critical g4 square. After hxg5 immediately, Qg4 is completely winning. }
21. Qxf1 { Forced. } 21... hxg5
{ This position has occurred no less than eight times in grandmaster play with all of them resulting in a draw. The piece capture is inferior in my opinion, but White needs to know how to proceed as this position is likely too difficult to find the winning chances over the board. Black may indeed have a defense that holds in the subsequent lines, but neither I, nor the engines, can seem to find it. }
22. Qf5
{ Threatening the e and g-pawns. The key to this position is knowing that White needs to take the g-pawn with the Knight when their Queen is on g4 and Black's Queen on f8 so that White gets a powerful discovery when the Knight moves or if the Queen blocks at g7 White gets Qe6+ when the Queen cannot block on f7. Black cannot stop this, but I will give the best attempt. }
22... Qd7
{ Black really wants to trade some material off when the extra piece would be decisive. }
23. Qg6+
{ Not Qxg5 ? which allows Black to trade the Queens off with Qg7 for a winning position. Qxe4 is enough to bail out for a draw if you want as Qxh3 gives up a perpetual since the Black King cannot step to the f-file when the Rook comes as enough reinforcement to mate Black. }
23... Qg7 24. Qe8+ Qf8 25. Qe6+ Qf7 26. Qc8+
{ We need the Queen on f8 so that it is not defending the e6 square which prevents Ne5 when we play Qg4. Furthermore, it allows a timely arrival of the Rook to f1 in some lines. }
26... Qf8 27. Qg4 { Now we get our Queen to g4. } 27... Qxd6 28. Nxg5
{ White is winning here.   28...Ne5  29.Qc8+  Kg7  30.Rf1  Nbd7  31.Qxa8  or   28...Qh6  29.Qc8+  Kg7  30.Qxb7  Kf6  31.Nxe4+  followed by Re1. }
