Qxd6
{ Only tried once in my database, but some guidance is probably a good idea given the scary central presense Black has acquired. }
15. fxe4
{ White won the only game played in this line with Kf2 ?, but Black is significantly better after h6. Instead, White can and should take the piece immediately with the better game. }
15... dxe4
{ Retaking on e4 is a most natural, but I will also briefly look at the check first as well. }
16. Bxg5
{ Developing before Black can play h6 when White's position can become difficult. Bg2 is a reasonable alternative, but appears to give no more than equality. Black has two dangerous pawns for the piece, but White is perfectly fine here. Black should probably either play h6 take the g5 square away from two White pieces or come on in with the check on g3. White has to come to grips that they will likely have to give back the piece for two pawns and a better position. If Black plays h6, then Bf4 should cause Black to play e5 and the Bishop can retreat to g3 and follow up with Bg2 and eventually Bf3 if Black pushes e3. White's King tends to walk to the kingside in the h6 variation. If Black plays the check on g3, the King needs to go to d2 and the Rook should come to g1 kicking the Queen out. White King will tend to walk to c1 an b1 in the Queen check lines. White will later release the Rook with a4. If and when White ends up giving the piece back for the two pawns, the board will be rather open and White will have at least one Bishop and fewer pawn islands than Black to provide some advantage with which to work. }
