[White "5. 6. ... Ne7 Systems"]
[Black "Ne7 with Nd7 Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Ne7
{ The Knight does not have a great future here if White does not take on g6 as it blocks in the Bishop. This is a fairly common reaction to Nge2 which clearly threatened to go to f4 hitting the Bishop. }
7. Nf4 { h4 first is met effectively with h5. } 7... Nd7
{ Black strives to maintain flexibility, but gives up breaking in the center which limits their counter-play. }
8. h4
{ Putting the question to the Bishop remains a standard theme in this line as well. }
8... h6 9. Nxg6
{ Grabbing the Bishop pair makes sense now since the Knight can be pushed back onto an inconvenient square blocking in the dark-square Bishop again. }
9... Nxg6
{ Clearly the best recapture as fxg6 comes under immediate pressure with Ne2 and Nf4. }
10. h5 { Pushing the Knight back to the e7 square that blocks in the Bishop. }
10... Ne7 { Essentially forced as Nh4 has no good prospects. } 11. Ne2
{ White anticipates the only logical continuation by Black which involves c5 and Nc6. }
11... c5 { Striking at the center is Black's best try. } 12. c3
{ White will take back with the c-pawn if Black captures when they will retain their space advantage and a natural plan forward usually involving f4. }
12... Nc6
{ Improving the Knight and clearing a path for the Bishop to develop. } 13. f4
{ Bolstering the e-pawn and eventually providing the option of f5 or g5 pawn breaks. White has a nice space advantage. The Bishop will usually develop to g2 and the King will castle short if allowed. This is a very rare line and it is not worth saying much more other than White will have easy development, the Bishop pair, and space to work. }
*

