[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. 6. ... Nd7 Systems"]
[Black "Nd7 with h5 Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Nd7
{ This move makes me think Black is aware of plans themself, but ignoring White's plan of h4 h5. }
7. h4 { Continuing with our kingside expansion with threat to the Bishop. }
7... h5
{ Not nearly as common as h6 in the Nd7 line, but it is a more active option. Black argues that with c5 left unplayed they can defend the Bishop with Ne7 and not have to worry about Nb5-Nd6 issues. Nonetheless, without the c5 break played, Black fails to generate enough counter-play and White can enter this line with confidence. }
8. Nf4
{ White either gets the h-pawn and Black having less counter-play than the c5 line after Bh7 or they get to trade the Knight for the Bishop if Black plays Ne7. }
8... Ne7 { Developing and defending the Bishop with a piece. } 9. Nxg6
{ Taking the influential Bishop off the board for a Knight. White has the Bishop pair, but it is not so valuable unless the center opens up. On a positive note, there is not much Black can do without opening the position either as their Knights have a lot of work to do to arrive at any good outposts. Moreover, White has ample space to more easily maneuver the Bishop pair. }
9... Nxg6
{ Taking with the Knight is the only consistent move fxg6 would be very weakening and provide a nice target upon which for White to focus. }
10. gxh5
{ g5 would be a positional mistake as the Knight on g6 can easily reroute to f5 through e7. Remember, we very rarely want to allow a Knight on f5 if the g-file is closed. }
10... Nxh4
{ The Knight still gets to f5 in due course, but with an open g-file and no h-pawn targeted, White gets their due counter-play. }
11. Bd3
{ Bd3 gives White the option to capture the Knight when it goes to f5 which would trade the Bishop pair for a structural advantage currently. }
11... c5
{ c5 threatens not only to break down the White center, but also c4 when the Bishop would have to move and give the Knight the nice outpost on f5. }
12. Qg4
{ The perfect answer. Threaten the Knight on h4 before the Bishop has to move and also pressuring g7 which helps keep the Bishop at home on f8. }
12... cxd4
{ Black elects to break up White's center, but their position is undeveloped and the Knight is rather loose. }
13. Ne2
{ Of course not Qxd4 ? which meets with Nf3+ and White loses the Queen. } 13...
Nf5
{ The most natural choice. However, g5 is quite interesting though not likely to be found over the board. }
14. Bxf5
{ A major advantage of the Bishop pair is the ability to more easily initiate exchanges. White takes Black's best developed piece and ruins their pawn structure. }
14... exf5 { Forced. } 15. Qxd4
{ Better than Qxf5 when g6 creates some counter-play. After Qxd4, White has the preferable position. Black's advised to give up the d-pawn and seek counter-play with Qc7 when White should take the d-pawn with pressure on the b and f-pawns and the preferable pawn structure. The White Bishop has flexible development, and the King will actually tend to remain in the center or walk to the kingside with a good endgame influence if the Queens are traded off. }
*

