1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Nd7
{ This move makes me think Black is aware of plans themself, but ignoring White's plan of h4 h5. }
7. h4 { Continuing with our kingside expansion with threat to the Bishop. }
7... h5
{ Not nearly as common as h6 in the Nd7 line, but it is a more active option. Black argues that with c5 left unplayed they can defend the Bishop with Ne7 and not have to worry about Nb5-Nd6 issues. Nonetheless, without the c5 break played, Black fails to generate enough counter-play and White can enter this line with confidence. }
8. Nf4
{ White either gets the h-pawn and Black having less counter-play than the c5 line after Bh7 or they get to trade the Knight for the Bishop if Black plays Ne7. }
8... Bh7
{ Trying to save the Bishop gives up the h-pawn for inadequate compensation. }
9. Nxh5
{ Now, Black can transpose to an inferior line of the c5 defense where Nd7 is worse than having the Knight on c6, or they can look in different paths. White has a fine game and Black is left trying to prove compensation for the lost pawn which will be pretty elusive. The light-square Bishop will go to b5 if c5 is played or g2 or d3, otherwise. The dark-square Bishop generally belongs on g5. f4 is thematic when c5 is played. The Queen tends to belong on d2 or f3. Castling long is common, but not always required. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. 6. ... Nd7 Systems"]
[Black "Nd7 with f6 Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Nd7
{ This move makes me think Black is aware of plans themself, but ignoring White's plan of h4 h5. }
7. h4 { Continuing with our kingside expansion with threat to the Bishop. }
7... f6
{ Black plays to immediately break up White's center. This is a dangerous policy given the lagging and impeded development. Furthermore, it is really not in the nature of a typical Caro-Kann player to create such tactically complex situations. I think the prepared White player can be quite happy with coming battle. }
8. h5
{ Little reason not to grab more space and force the Bishop to a less active post. }
8... Bf7 { Be4 is just bad for Black after Nxe4. } 9. f4
{ White defends the e-pawn. } 9... c5
{ Black has to find a way to fight back and c5 looks to be the only source of counter-play. }
10. Qd3
{ White develops the Queen and prepares to castle long. Often, the Queen will be well placed on f3 or g3. }
10... a6
{ Black's play is on the queenside, but they are moving pawns while White is improving pieces. White will have the option to castle queenside soon, but nothing requires it. Note Qb6 is answered by Be3. Ne7 is also an idea that I will briefly cover. }
11. Bg2
{ Now that Bb5 is not likely, the Bishop is placed on the long diagonal for long-term purposes. White has space, options to open lines, options to castle either way soon, and no seriously restricted pieces, unlike Black. I find White preferable here and think this is sufficient to recommend the line. }
*

