[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Nd7
{ This move makes me think Black is aware of plans themself, but ignoring White's plan of h4 h5. }
7. h4 { Continuing with our kingside expansion with threat to the Bishop. }
7... f6
{ Black plays to immediately break up White's center. This is a dangerous policy given the lagging and impeded development. Furthermore, it is really not in the nature of a typical Caro-Kann player to create such tactically complex situations. I think the prepared White player can be quite happy with coming battle. }
8. h5
{ Little reason not to grab more space and force the Bishop to a less active post. }
8... Bf7 { Be4 is just bad for Black after Nxe4. } 9. f4
{ White defends the e-pawn. } 9... c5
{ Black has to find a way to fight back and c5 looks to be the only source of counter-play. }
10. Qd3
{ White develops the Queen and prepares to castle long. Often, the Queen will be well placed on f3 or g3. }
10... Ne7
{ Black elects to work on the development of pieces finally. The Knight has a natural square on c6, but they are spending a lot of time. }
11. exf6
{ Now that the King's Knight cannot recapture on f6, it is an opportune moment to capture and open some lines. }
11... gxf6
{ Surely the best recapture which gives the Bishop on f8 hope of some freedom and leaves the Knight on d7 defending the c-pawn. }
12. Bd2
{ Preparing to castle long now that we have promise of opening the center. Bg2 also looks promising. Black's position is tightly packed and it is difficult to get in, but it is White seeking an opening and Black defending. As long as White does not let the center pawns get out of control and rolling, they have a promising game with which to look forward. Note, dxc5 trying to win a pawn, is too ambitious and Black ends up with a fine game after Nc6 instead of immediately recapturing. The general approach will be to play the g5 break when, if Black pushes to f5, they will have a backward and weak e-pawn and the Bishop on f7 effectively out of the game for a long time. If Black does not push by, then more lines open up for White. Castling long will normally occur at some point and the Bishop will usually end up on g2. The best square for the Queen, especially if Black hits it with c4, is usually either f3 or h3. Black is probably ok here, but White's game seems easier to play. }
*

