1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Nd7
{ This move makes me think Black is aware of plans themself, but ignoring White's plan of h4 h5. }
7. h4 { Continuing with our kingside expansion with threat to the Bishop. }
7... f6
{ Black plays to immediately break up White's center. This is a dangerous policy given the lagging and impeded development. Furthermore, it is really not in the nature of a typical Caro-Kann player to create such tactically complex situations. I think the prepared White player can be quite happy with coming battle. }
8. h5
{ Little reason not to grab more space and force the Bishop to a less active post. }
8... Bf7 { Be4 is just bad for Black after Nxe4. } 9. f4
{ White defends the e-pawn. } 9... fxe5
{ Immediately trying to break down the White pawn center has its point. } 10.
fxe5
{ Taking back with the f-pawn minimizes Black's counter-play by not allowing any immediate d4 ideas. Furthermore, and open f-file may prove rather dangerous for Black's King. }
10... c5
{ Continuing to undermine the White center makes sense especially since White no longer has an f-pawn to defend the new e-pawn. }
11. Qd3
{ A novelty which grants the White Queen quick access to f3 or g3 as needed. }
11... cxd4 { Black tries to win a pawn. It will be expensive. } 12. Nxd4
{ Taking with the Knight which will add pressure to the c6 square if Black tries to take the pawn and retreat. }
12... Nxe5 { A dangerous pawn grab. } 13. Qg3
{ Immediately putting pressure on the Knight. } 13... Bd6
{ The natural attempt to defend has problems. } 14. Bf4
{ Black is in real trouble as   14...Nc4  is met with  15.Bxc4  Bxf4  14.Bb5+  or   14...Qb8  15.Bb5+  Kf8  16.O-O. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. 6. ... Nd7 Systems"]
[Black "Nd7 with h6 Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Nd7
{ This move makes me think Black is aware of plans themself, but ignoring White's plan of h4 h5. }
7. h4 { Continuing with our kingside expansion with threat to the Bishop. }
7... h6
{ Black gives themself a retreat, but again h6, which is by far the most popular move in this position, is a bit passive as opposed to h5 or f6. }
8. Be3
{ This offers a favorable transposition to the 6. . .. c5 line, but Black has tried a variety of other moves. }
8... Bb4
{ I cannot hardly express how much joy I feel when Black plays Bb4 in this opening. Black is apparently willing to either trade their dark-square Bishop  (note on what color that all the Black center pawns are located)  for White's least aggressive piece, or to leave it out of play on the queenside. }
9. h5
{ It turns out that we need to play this move first to either lure the Bishop to the more exposed e4 square or push it back to the h7 square which will impede the Rook from participating for the moment. }
9... Bh7
{ Playing the classical retreat to h7 is the obvious first move to consider. }
10. a3
{ Now we put the question to the Bishop. If Be7, then White gets in a3 for free. If Ba5, then the Bishop is out of play and at the right moment b4 may kill any c5 counter-play  (at the expense of allowing a5)  . If Bxc3, we get the Bishop pair which is not particularly advantageous at the moment with the blocked center, but f4 is ready to go to get things opening up. }
10... Bxc3+ { Likely the best try for Black. } 11. Nxc3
{ The engines do not like bxc3 much claiming Black is roughly equal. However, I will tell you I have won a number of games with bxc3 as White's King tends to be safe in the center and the attack with f4 tends to be faster. bxc3 recaptures tend to be even better if Black has allowed the g-pawns to get doubled. I have played both moves with favorable results. I will give Nxc3 as the recommendation, but feel free to mix it up for variety and surprise value with bxc3. }
11... Qb6 { Focusing on White's tender b-pawn. } 12. Na4
{ The Knight really has no future elsewhere anytime soon, so I recommend using it to push the Queen back  (or off the board)  and exerting some control over the c5 square. }
12... Qc7
{ The retreat is logical as Black can look to castle long and argue that the Knight on a4 is misplaced. Nonetheless, Black's position still has problems and they are lacking for space and development. }
13. f4
{ White has a stable advantage and has a selection of promising plans including Bd3 with f5 or Qd2 with g5. White will normally castle long, if at all, and Black faces problems with castling on either direction. If Black castles long, they have difficulty generating any counter-play without great risk. If Black castles short, it is into an attack so they usually should stay in the center as long as viable. }
*

