{ Playing the classical retreat to h7 is the obvious first move to consider. }
10. a3
{ Now we put the question to the Bishop. If Be7, then White gets in a3 for free. If Ba5, then the Bishop is out of play and at the right moment b4 may kill any c5 counter-play  (at the expense of allowing a5)  . If Bxc3, we get the Bishop pair which is not particularly advantageous at the moment with the blocked center, but f4 is ready to go to get things opening up. }
10... Bxc3+ { Likely the best try for Black. } 11. Nxc3
{ The engines do not like bxc3 much claiming Black is roughly equal. However, I will tell you I have won a number of games with bxc3 as White's King tends to be safe in the center and the attack with f4 tends to be faster. bxc3 recaptures tend to be even better if Black has allowed the g-pawns to get doubled. I have played both moves with favorable results. I will give Nxc3 as the recommendation, but feel free to mix it up for variety and surprise value with bxc3. }
11... Qb6 { Focusing on White's tender b-pawn. } 12. Na4
{ The Knight really has no future elsewhere anytime soon, so I recommend using it to push the Queen back  (or off the board)  and exerting some control over the c5 square. }
12... Qa5+
{ Black seeks some counter-play and the opportunity to castle queenside if allowed. }
13. Qd2
{ Surprising moves are always unsettling. c3 or Nc3 are perfectly adequate as well. Qxa4 loses the Queen to b3. If Black retreats we developed our Queen for free. If Black trades Queens, then our King is well-placed in the center after Kxd2, and our plan of f4 with extra space should provide a nice advantage going forward as Black still faces development problems. }
