1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Nd7
{ This move makes me think Black is aware of plans themself, but ignoring White's plan of h4 h5. }
7. h4 { Continuing with our kingside expansion with threat to the Bishop. }
7... h6
{ Black gives themself a retreat, but again h6, which is by far the most popular move in this position, is a bit passive as opposed to h5 or f6. }
8. Be3
{ This offers a favorable transposition to the 6. . .. c5 line, but Black has tried a variety of other moves. }
8... Qc7
{ A relatively rare line, but quite a logical one. Black adds more support to the c5 break and creates the opportunity to castle long. }
9. h5 { It is useful to take away h5 from Black's options. } 9... Bh7
{ Much better than allowing White to play Nxe4 after Be4. } 10. f4
{ White naturally plays to threaten f5 while grabbing even more space to inhibit comfortable development of Black's kingside. }
10... O-O-O
{ Black has a lot of alternatives, but this is the most consistent move after Qc7. }
11. a3
{ A useful move to keep the Bishop and Knight fighting over the e7 square for development. White has such an advantage brewing on the kingside that the simplest plan to go with against such a rare line is to castle long themself so that any play attempted against White's King would open up Black's King to an attack as well. If Black does not attack on the queenside, then the play is on the side that White has the better position and maneuverability. White is better here, but they need to take their time and slowly improve as Black's position is cramped but solid. Typically, White will play Qd2, O-O-O, Bg2 or Bh3 and then look for a favorable f-pawn break. If Black gets aggressive on the queenside then a timely Rook lift to h3 will often have Black regretting the aggression. }
