1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Nd7
{ This move makes me think Black is aware of plans themself, but ignoring White's plan of h4 h5. }
7. h4 { Continuing with our kingside expansion with threat to the Bishop. }
7... h6
{ Black gives themself a retreat, but again h6, which is by far the most popular move in this position, is a bit passive as opposed to h5 or f6. }
8. Be3
{ This offers a favorable transposition to the 6. . .. c5 line, but Black has tried a variety of other moves. }
8... Be7
{ Black tries to make White commit the g or h-pawn to reduce their options. In reality, White has multiple options to choose from here. Nf4, h5, and a3 all offer promising opportunities. I am going to recommend Nf4 which is the most consistent with other lines. Objectively speaking though, h5 may very well prove to be the strongest for those that want to venture into other areas. }
9. Nf4 { Seek active play by gaining a tempo on the Bishop. } 9... Bh7
{ As in so many lines, Black retreats the Bishop to avoid a terrible structure on the kingside. }
10. Bd3
{ Now that Black spent a tempo playing Bh7, we encourage them to spend another to play Bxd3 and develop our Queen. If Black does not take the White Bishop, then White will take the Black Bishop and play Qd3 hitting the Rook and getting the tempo anyway ! Again, the h-pawn is not so important in this line as it opens up the file for our Rook. }
10... Bxd3
{ Black tries to ease their position with a piece trade. I will look at obvious try, Bxh4, as well. }
11. Qxd3
{ Naturally recapturing with the Queen and preparing to quickly castle long. }
11... Bxh4
{ Black decides to at least get a pawn for their misery. Other moves will be met with a similar plan of castling long and playing Nh5 and sometimes f4 or g5 or both. White has a winning attack in all tries. }
12. Nh5
{ Either getting the pawn back with advantage or creating more weaknesses or often both. The King can no longer castle away. }
12... g6 { This is no better, indeed it is even worse than g5. } 13. Ng7+
{ The tactics favor White here. } 13... Kf8
{ Ke7 blocks the Bishop defender allowing Rxh4. } 14. Nxe6+
{ White will get three pawns for the Knight and the King is dangerously exposed. }
14... fxe6 { Forced. } 15. Qxg6
{ Black cannot comfortably hold the e6 pawn and the Bishop on h4 leaving White with a winning position. Qe7 is met with O-O-O and Black is paralyzed while White brings more guns to bear on the Black King. }
