1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Nd7
{ This move makes me think Black is aware of plans themself, but ignoring White's plan of h4 h5. }
7. h4 { Continuing with our kingside expansion with threat to the Bishop. }
7... h6
{ Black gives themself a retreat, but again h6, which is by far the most popular move in this position, is a bit passive as opposed to h5 or f6. }
8. Be3
{ This offers a favorable transposition to the 6. . .. c5 line, but Black has tried a variety of other moves. }
8... Be7
{ Black tries to make White commit the g or h-pawn to reduce their options. In reality, White has multiple options to choose from here. Nf4, h5, and a3 all offer promising opportunities. I am going to recommend Nf4 which is the most consistent with other lines. Objectively speaking though, h5 may very well prove to be the strongest for those that want to venture into other areas. }
9. Nf4 { Seek active play by gaining a tempo on the Bishop. } 9... Bxh4
{ A mistake that plays into White's hands. Black's light-square complex will be very weak and White will have plenty of compensation for the pawn. }
10. Nxg6
{ Taking the Bishop when fxg6 is required is nearly always the correct move. }
10... fxg6 { Forced. } 11. Bd3
{ Immediately pressuring the weak g6 pawn/ square. } 11... g5
{ Trying to hold on to the pawn is problematic. } 12. Bg6+
{ Forcing the King to remain in a vulnerable position. } 12... Ke7
{ The only square that does not just drop material immediately. } 13. Qd2
{ White prepares to castle when f4 becomes a threat. The Queen is also prepared to go to b4 after Na4. In short, Black has too many problems if they try to save the g-pawn with g5. White already has a winning position. }
