1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Nd7
{ This move makes me think Black is aware of plans themself, but ignoring White's plan of h4 h5. }
7. h4 { Continuing with our kingside expansion with threat to the Bishop. }
7... h6
{ Black gives themself a retreat, but again h6, which is by far the most popular move in this position, is a bit passive as opposed to h5 or f6. }
8. Be3
{ This offers a favorable transposition to the 6. . .. c5 line, but Black has tried a variety of other moves. }
8... Ne7
{ This makes more sense in this position since White cannot play Nb5 and drop in on the d6 square unlike in the c5 line. However, White has not committed to Nf4 yet which means the backup plan actually works well here. }
9. f4
{ Immediately seeking to open up the center for which White is better prepared. }
9... h5
{ Black should just retreat the Bishop now with an inferior position and few prospects. h5 has been the most common choice albeit in a limited number of games. }
10. f5
{ A critical decision and one White must understand in many lines of this opening. White almost never wants to allow a Black Knight to get to f5 which g5 would allow at the moment. Better is to momentarily sacrifice a pawn to keep the Knight off of f5 and to seal in the Bishop. }
10... exf5 { Black has serious problems if they do not accept the pawn. } 11.
g5
{ Now White will play Nf4 making the Knight on e7 and the Bishop on g6 quite poor pieces. Therefore, Black should give the pawn back with f4. }
11... f4
{ Black really cannot try to hold onto a pawn that makes two pieces horrible. }
12. Nxf4
{ Now, White either favorably takes the Bishop on g6 or gets Bh3 advantageously. If Black gets the desirable Knight on f5, which White rarely wants to allow, White is doing quite well after Bf2. White has the superior position. }
