[Black "6. ... Na6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Na6
{ Very rare. I will provide a straightforward response and leave it at that. }
7. Nf4 { Consistent with our normal plans to harass the Bishop on g6. } 7...
Ne7 { Developing and defending the Bishop. } 8. Be3
{ Na6 is intended to support a c5 push or an invasion to b4 attacking the c2 square. Since Nf4 takes away any c2 issues, Black's plan is to play c5 so adding coverage to c5 with Be3 is most logical. }
8... c5
{ Played anyway as if White captures then Nc6 pressures the weakened e-pawn. White is ok in this line, but the recommended response looks even stronger. }
9. Nb5
{ Remember, anytime Ne7 and c5 have been played, Nb5 heading to d6 should at least be a candidate move. }
9... Nc6 { Black has to stop Nd6 and pressuring d4 is the best way. } 10. c3
{ White adds support to the d-pawn and will normally take the Bishop on g6 on the next move leaving White with a comfortable advantage. Note, if Black plays   10...cxd4  , the correct reply here is  11.Nxd4  when  11...Nxe5  is brutally punished by  12.Bb5+  Nd7  13.Ndxe6  fxe6  14.Nxe6  Qe7  15.Qxd5  Bf7  16.Qxb7  Rb8  17.Nc7+  Nxc7  18.Qxb8+  Qd8  19.Bxd7+  Kxd7  20.O-O-O  Bd6  12.Rxd6+  Kxd6  13.Rd1+  Bd5  14.Qxa7  Ke6  15.Bf4  and White will recoup both pieces, usually involving a  c4  pawn push, and have more pawns for the endgame. }
