1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... a6
{ a6 is very rare and designed to keep a piece, especially the Bishop, off of b5, but it is very slow and White gets a nice advantage with normal play. }
7. h4 { Standard Bishop threatening. } 7... h6
{ More active plans with the h5 plan are too ambitious when effectively down a tempo with a6. }
8. h5 { Taking the space with tempo. } 8... Bh7 { Saving the piece. } 9. Be3
{ White will play f4 and Bg2, then can castle either way at their discretion and eventually seek to open the position up with f5 or g5. Black has a solid position, but lacking in any significant counter-play. White simply needs to be patient and slowly improve the position. }
