{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Qb6
{ This move acknowledges White's initiative on the kingside and seeks to pressure the center and b-pawn while preparing Black's King to run away to the queenside. }
7. h4
{ Our standard forcing move that gains space on the side of the board we have the initiative. }
7... h6
{ Providing sanctuary for the Bishop without creating open lines or weaknesses that h5 would entail. }
8. h5
{ Taking more space. Nf4 just gets in the way as White normally plays for f4 in the sideline variations. }
8... Bh7 { The obvious retreat. } 9. f4
{ Securing the e-pawn if Black plays any central breaks and keeping options to play f5 at some point. }
9... Nd7 { The most consistent follow-up which allows queenside castling. } 10.
Rh3
{ Taking maximum advantage of the extra space. White is prepared to swing the Rook as needed. Castling long when an extra Rook might appear in the area while all Black's kingside pieces are clustered up may be asking for trouble. }
10... O-O-O
{ Premature. Black draws the battleground, but White is better prepared for it. }
11. b3
{ White needs to release the Bishop for duty. After b3, the Queen on b6 looks misplaced. More to the point, White can place the Bishop on b2 when it helps hold the center together without getting in the way of any later Rook moves along the third rank. Black has some various moves from here each leaving White with a small advantage. After Bb2, White can usually either play Qd2 and castle long for a more positional game where both sides have about even chances or can play more aggressively with Na4 pushing the Queen back to c7 and then advancing on the queenside with b4 and leaving the King in the center. }
