[White "7. Move 6 Sidelines for Black"]
[Black "6. ...Qh4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Qh4
{ A tricky line that outright denies White the plan of h4-h5. Sometimes employed at the club-level as a surprise weapon, but frankly not very good. White gets a great game with simple moves as the Queen is too aggressively offsides and it will show soon enough. }
7. h3
{ Nf4 is also adequate to answer this plan by Black, but it tends to be a bit sharper and this is not played often enough to invest a lot of sharp theory into learning it. }
7... Bb4 8. a3
{ White will follow up with Be3 and Rg1 when Black's plan just looks silly as White will be able to castle soon and the Black Queen will get bullied around only expediting White's kingside play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Move 6 Sidelines for Black"]
[Black "6. ... h5 Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... h5
{ Not particularly common, but players that are unfamiliar with this opening may play the move order wrong knowing the h5 is the key defense, but forgetting that c5 needs to be played first ! }
7. Nf4
{ The correct way to punish the premature h-pawn push as Black no longer has a good defense without c5 and h4 thrown in. }
7... Ne7
{ Probably the best try, but White seizes a nice advantage here as well. } 8.
Nxg6 { Giving Black an unpleasant choice of recaptures. } 8... Nxg6
{ fxg ? is even worse after Bg5 really ties Black in knots. } 9. gxh5
{ Winning a pawn for no discernable compensation. } 9... Nh4
{ Ne7 runs into Bg5 again, but this is not much better as White gets very comfortable development and a significant advantage. }
10. Qg4
{ White will castle long and have all the play in the position. Note that after a move such as   11...c5  the immediate  12.Bg5  loses to  Qxg5  as capturing with  13.Qxg5  allows  Nf3+  netting a piece for free  . Therefore, the Bishops will tend to go to f4 or e3 and d3 or b5. Once White gets castled long, the Bg5 tactic becomes viable. }
