[Black "6. ... h5 Variation #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... h5
{ Not particularly common, but players that are unfamiliar with this opening may play the move order wrong knowing the h5 is the key defense, but forgetting that c5 needs to be played first ! }
7. Nf4
{ The correct way to punish the premature h-pawn push as Black no longer has a good defense without c5 and h4 thrown in. }
7... Qh4
{ Completely inadequate with the Knight already on f4. White is already winning. }
8. Nxg6
{ Taking a piece off and creating a weakness at g6 quickly proves the Queen sortie is ineffectual. }
8... fxg6 { Forced. } 9. Ne2
{ This move highlights all the weaknesses of Black's position. The Knight intends to go to f4 when g6 and e6 are targeted. If Black plays g5, the Queen is locked out of play and the Knight acts as a phenomenal blockader on g3. }
9... g5
{ The best try, but White's activity reaches great levels very quickly. } 10.
Qd3 { Threatening Qb3 and Qg6. } 10... hxg4
{ Allowing the Queen to retreat and participate, but now the Irish pawns on the g-file are a severe problem in the long term. Ne7 instead and White has a pleasant choice of gxh4 or Qb3. }
11. Ng3
{ Black's position is a mess. White has a decisive advantage. Black's best line is   11...Qh7  12.Qb3  g6  13.Bxg5  where White has regained the pawn and still has the better position with plenty of weaknesses to target. Note alternative lines will be even better for White as White always has the option of playing an effective h3 to win the g-pawn or Qd1 with Be2 to win the g-pawn a different way after which Black's position has nothing but weaknesses to target and pieces placed in inconvenient squares. }
