1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... h5
{ Not particularly common, but players that are unfamiliar with this opening may play the move order wrong knowing the h5 is the key defense, but forgetting that c5 needs to be played first ! }
7. Nf4
{ The correct way to punish the premature h-pawn push as Black no longer has a good defense without c5 and h4 thrown in. }
7... Bh7 { The typical retreat runs into an atypical problem in this line. } 8.
g5
{ White can also play Nxh5 for an advantage when they can try to transpose to lines they know well after c5 and h4, but g5 is stronger here as the h-pawn may fall to the Queen when the pin on the h7 Bishop to the Rook opens a lot of possibilities for White. After Bf5, White gets a great position with either g6 or Nxh5. If g6 instead, the Bishop is buried for a long time. Obviously, Qxg5 is met with Nxe6 and White trades the Knight off for the important dark-square Bishop on f8. Ne7 is met with Qxh5 with a vice grip on Black's position. }
