[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Move 6 Sidelines for Black"]
[Black "6. ... Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Be7
{ Uncommon, but logical. Be7 seeks to prevent h4 while still developing. The problem is the Knight on g8 is very restricted and this creates some challenges for Black to complete development. White should simply continue to develop normally when Black eventually runs out of easy moves and has the problem of what to do with the Knight. It can develop to h6, but after h3, it is not such a great piece. }
7. Be3
{ Allowing for Qd2 which will stop Nh6 and enable queenside castling very quickly. }
7... Nd7
{ Likewise, Black develops and prepares to castle queenside in some lines. From d7, the Knight supports both natural pawn breaks, c5 and f6. }
8. Nf4
{ I prefer the direct method of threatening the Bishop, but not taking it until it gives itself an escape. This will make castling long much safer when White can proceed forward with queenside play or strive to open up the center for the Bishops. More common in this rare line is Qd2 which is sufficient for an edge as well. White is ready to castle and Nh6 is essentially off the table. Another common try for White is Ng3 which puts influence on the h5 square and supports an f4-f5 advance when White is ready. The Ng3 plan would be my second choice, but Nf4 is just so natural in this opening and I see no reason not to play it here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Move 6 Sidelines for Black"]
[Black "6. ... Bb4 Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Bb4
{ Bb4 is always a welcome sight. The Bishop will either concede the Bishop pair or end up committed to the queenside when White is playing mostly on the kingside. }
7. h4 { Grabbing space with the threat to the Bishop. } 7... h6
{ Black provides themself with an escape for the Bishop. } 8. h5
{ The move Be3 here is not as strong as when Black has played Nd7 before Bb4. Therefore, we grab the space and fall back on plans involving f4. }
8... Bh7
{ As is so often the case, if Black plays Be4 and White cannot capture due to a pin, and cannot play f3, then the best square for the Rook is to go to h3. }
9. a3
{ We want to know Black's intention with the Bishop. Retreating either takes the e7 square from the Knight or removes the Bishop's influence from the kingside. Capturing concedes the Bishop pair when White has a natural opening break with f4- f5. I am always happy when I see Bb4 played as it invariably forces Black to make a decision with a downside. }
9... Ba5
{ Black tries to keep the Bishop, but now it has lost influence over the c5 square and the kingside. }
10. Be3
{ White increases the prophylaxis against c5 with intent to play for f4 and will usually castle long. }
10... Nd7
{ Black plays to support c5 and f6 breaks, pressure on e5 if White played dxc5, and prepares to castle long. }
11. f4
{ White shores up defense of e5 thus undermining the c5 break again. In general, White will play Qd2, Bg2 or Bh3 and castle in possibly either direction followed by working toward either an f5 of a b3- c4 pawn break to open the board up. }
