1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2
{ This is our starting point for all variations covered in this book. See the Introduction chapter for discussion of this and all prior moves. }
6... Bb4
{ Bb4 is always a welcome sight. The Bishop will either concede the Bishop pair or end up committed to the queenside when White is playing mostly on the kingside. }
7. h4 { Grabbing space with the threat to the Bishop. } 7... Be4
{ All centralized pieces are not favorable. The Bishop will ultimately be traded off favorably or forced to retreat and actualizing a loss of tempo versus traditional lines. }
8. Rh3
{ A standard move anytime White cannot immediately capture on e4 or play a defended f3. The Rook will eventually be of use on a variety of files. }
8... h5
{ Seeking to activate the Rook, but it will ultimately be insufficient. } 9.
Ng3
{ Black is lagging in development and likely to go down a pawn with no compensation. An example of further play can be seen in Vasiukov vs. Razuvaev in the Master Games chapter. }
