[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Master Games (Annotated)"]
[Black "Kasparov, Garry vs. Karpov, Anatoly"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let us begin our master games section featuring possibly the greatest Caro-Kann player of modern times. Even the great Karpov succumbs to this opening ! }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2 Ne7 7. Nf4 c5 8. dxc5
{ This is the first departure from the theory section. This is a major alternative to the recommended h4. The h4 line recommended in this course ran into a drawish sequence at the GM level after major fireworks. I believe I have found a way around the draw in that line that significantly favors White. Nonetheless, if you find that line too challenging, then this is a path for further investigation by the reader. }
8... Nd7
{ Nec6 is more typical in this line. This may end up transposing, but the knight on e7 usually needs to go to c6 in most of these lines in order to release the bishop on f8. }
9. h4
{ Standard follow-up which compels Black to deal with the threat to the bishop. }
9... Nxe5 10. Bg2
{ Bb5+ is more typical, but Kasparov plays something new. Likely this was a prepared deviation to take Karpov into unprepared territory. }
10... h5
{ This gives White a nice initiative and advantage. d4 was the only way to hold onto equality. }
11. Qe2
{ Creating multiple immediate threats including sacrifices on the d-pawn after Nxg6. }
11... N7c6
{ Better than Nxg4 which allows our standard theme of Nb5 to threaten to drop in on d6 which forces N7c6 when the bishop will fall on g6 and be forced to recapture with the f-pawn. }
12. Nxg6 { Taking the bishop without any further delay. } 12... Nxg6 13. Bg5
{ Capturing the d-pawn is tempting, but Bxc5 or hxg are both promising answers. Finishing development and threatening to add the queen's rook to the fight is more challenging to answer. }
13... Be7
{ The most logical defense which relieves the e-pawn to defend the d-pawn and develops his last minor. }
14. gxh5 Nf8
{ This fails to pose White any challenges. The best try here was Nxh4 and, while Black is still worse, he is still fighting. }
15. Nb5 { Threatening to play Nd6+. Also strong is Rd1 !? } 15... Nd7
{ Nd6+ ? now lets Black escape with Kf8 and the knight is unstable as Nxc5 is threatened. }
16. h6
{ A fantastic move. g6 weakens the dark squares after Bxe7. If the king then White just castles long and the king hunt begins. If the knight takes then simply castling and the knight cannot take on c5 as Qe5 threatens the king's rook decisively. If the queen takes, then Nc7+ picks up the rook on a8. If Black takes on h6, then Nd6+ Kf8 Qh5 is decisive. }
16... Nxc5
{ Probably the best try, but Black's position is becoming precariously loose. }
17. Bf4
{ Highlighting the weak dark-squares in Black's center. hxg7 should also win. }
17... Kf8 { Nothing else is better, but surely cannot save Black's position. }
18. hxg7+
{ Castling first is just as strong, but the immediate capture is more forcing. }
18... Kxg7 19. O-O-O Kf8 20. Kb1
{ Tucking away the king for more safety before launching the final assault. This also prepares for a c4 break to rip the center open. Leaving the king on the c-file might provide some counter-play if c4 was played. }
20... a6
{ Losing immediately to a nice combination. Qa5 or Qb6 seeking some counter-play were Black's best tries albeit they are insufficient at this point. }
21. Nc7
{ The d-pawn is now under a lot of pressure and a sacrifice is eminent. } 21...
Rc8 22. Bxd5 { Nxd5 is also winning. } 22... exd5 23. Rxd5 Qxc7
{ Three pieces is not enough for a queen and two pawns, but there is nothing better here. }
24. Bxc7 Rxc7 25. Rf5
{ White is clearly winning here. The rest of the moves are provided without comment. This will create problems with keeping any piece coordination with Qc4 threatening mate. }
25... Rd7 26. c3 f6 27. Rg1 Nd8 28. Qg4 Ke8 29. Rh5 Rf8 30. Rxc5 Bxc5 31. Qh5+
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Master Games (Annotated)"]
[Black "Vasiukov, Evgeni vs. Razuvaev, Yuri S"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2 Bb4 7. h4 Be4 8. Rh3 h5
9. Ng3
{ This is the last move provided in our theoretical section. White is already significantly better already. }
9... c5
{ Black tries to break up White's center as quickly as possible. However, he has inadequate development to support such an endeavor and it will quickly fail to impress. }
10. Bg5
{ a3 is likely a more direct refutation, but development is also sufficient for an advantage. }
10... f6
{ Qa5 instead is easily met with Nxh5. f6 opens up the position, but it is White that is better prepared for an attack. }
11. Bd2
{ exf6 immediately is stronger, but Bd2 is sufficient to maintain the initiative that White is developing. }
11... Bxc3 { Bg6 is a better try. } 12. bxc3 Nc6 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Nxe4 dxe4
15. Qe2
{ A key move to allow the queenside Rook to join the fight while simultaneously pressuring the weakened Black pawns. }
15... Qd7
{ This is too passive. While White has a significant advantage after all alternatives, better was to try to play more actively with cxd4 or Qd5. }
16. Qxe4 O-O-O 17. g5
{ O-O-O is also sufficient for a nice advantage, but g5 stabilizes the position with White up a pawn. }
17... Nge7
{ This just exacerbates the problems Black has. Necessary was to play f5 and try to fight a pawn down. }
18. gxf6
{ No reason not to take the second pawn which makes Black's situation more desperate. }
18... Nf5 19. Rd3
{ Strong enough, but I prefer castling long when Black's counter-play is essentially cut to zero. }
19... cxd4 20. cxd4 Rhg8
{ After this, Black has no chances. A better try was to play Rhf8 and try to get one of the pawns back. The rest is given with minimal commentary as the game is effectively over now. }
21. Bg5 Nb4 22. Rd2 Kb8 23. Rb1 { d5 is even stronger. } 23... Nd5 24. c4 Nb6
25. c5 Nd5 26. Rdb2 Ka8 27. f7 Qxf7 28. Bxd8 Rxd8 29. Rxb7 Qf6 30. Qd3
{ With the threat of Qa6, White now has mate in 4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Master Games (Annotated)"]
[Black "Shirov, Alexei vs. Bareev, Evgeny"]
[Result "*"]

{ How could I possibly not include a game or two of the variation's namesake ? }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2 Ne7 7. Nf4 c5 8. dxc5
{ This is a major alternative to our recommended h4 covered in the theory section. See the theory section for commentary on moves prior to this move. dxc5 is a logical move in the position, but I believe h4 is stronger. dxc5 opens the position up while Black remains somewhat undeveloped. However, it costs a valuable tempo and solves Black's most pertinent problem of the Knight and the Bishop fighting for use of the e7-square. }
8... Nec6 { Clearing the way for the Bishop and pressuring the e-pawn. } 9. h4
{ A forcing move as the Bishop is in jeopardy. } 9... Qc7
{ The most aggressive try. Nxe5 is likely better, but both h5 or Bg2 are good retorts from White. }
10. Bg2
{ White plays for maximum development and coverage of the e4 square. The immediate h5 may even be stronger. }
10... Qxe5+
{ The most natural continuation which either compels White to retreat a Knight with Nfe2 or Nce2 or forego castling with Kf1. Shirov elects the later. }
11. Kf1 d4 12. h5
{ White judges that a quick opening of lines will favor his position and that the Bishop on g6 is playing more of a role than the Knight on c3. }
12... Bxc2
{ This will only speed up White's attack by clearing the back rank for a Rook to get to the open files faster than leaving the Queen in the way. }
13. Qxc2 dxc3 14. Nd3
{ Order is not important as White will play Nd3 and Be3. } 14... Qd4 15. Be3
Qc4 16. Qxc3
{ White has to go ahead and allow the Queens to trade off, but he has such a superior development that the advantage is quite significant due to the weak b-pawn after the b-file opens up. }
16... Qxc3 17. bxc3 Na6
{ Na5 probably offers a bit more resistance. Nonetheless, Black's position is untenable. }
18. Rb1 O-O-O 19. Bxc6
{ Arguably, it would be stronger to just defend the Knight with Ke2 or Be4 first and try to rapidly bring the other Rook into the fight, but this is enough to hold the advantage as it wins at least a pawn. }
19... bxc6 20. Ne5 { Dual threats to c6 and f7 are too much to handle. } 20...
Rg8 21. Nxf7 Rd7 22. Ne5 { Nd6 is just as strong. } 22... Rb7 23. Rxb7 Kxb7 24.
Nd3 e5 25. Ke2 { Time to improve the King and bring the Rook into the game. }
25... Be7 26. Kf3
{ The King is a mighty piece and will soon be a major threat to the e-pawn. }
26... Kc7 27. Ke4 Re8 28. Rh3
{ The Rook will go to the vulnerable f-file when penetration cannot be stopped and the game will conclude soon. }
28... Kd7 29. Nxe5+ Kc7 30. Rf3 Bf6 31. Rf5 h6 32. f4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Master Games (Annotated)"]
[Black "Svidler, Peter vs. Renet, Olivier"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2 c5 7. h4 h5 8. Nf4 Bh7
9. Nxh5 cxd4 10. Nb5 Nc6 11. Nxd4 Nge7 12. c3 a6
{ This is the first move not discussed in detail in our theory section. For moves up to this point see the theory section. }
13. Rh3
{ Nxc6 followed by Bg5 is more consistent. Rh3 is a logical attempt to try to bring more pieces into the fight, but it is a little too slow to maintain the initiative. }
13... Nxe5 14. Bg5 Qc7 15. Re3
{ This allows Black to castle long and evade most of White's activity. Bf4 or Qe2 with pressure on the Knight on e5 makes more sense here. Re3 puts pressure on the Knight, but does not allow White to bring the Queen's Rook into the game as quickly. }
15... O-O-O 16. Nf4 { Bf4 is more consistent. } 16... Nc4
{ Black misses his chance for a significant advantage with Rd7. Black needs to relieve the pin on the Knight on e7 so the Bishop can develop. Once Black gets in Nc6 and develops the dark-square Bishop they will have no problems and can even claim an advantage from the better central pawn presence. }
17. Bxc4 dxc4 18. Qe2
{ White mistakenly plays to hold up an e5 push. Better was Qf3 when e5 is answered by Nfe6 or Nde6. Now, Black has another chance to find and play the strong Rd7. }
18... Bd3
{ Black sees tactic based on e5 if White captures on d3, but White has seen more clearly. Rd7 and Black retains the advantage. }
19. Nxd3 cxd3 20. Rxd3 e5 21. O-O-O
{ White takes advantage of the superior piece development for a decisive sacrifice. }
21... exd4 22. Rxd4 Rxd4 23. Rxd4 b5
{ Trying to keep the Rook off of c4, but this weakens the a8-h1 diagonal. Other tries are no better. }
24. Qe4 Qc6 25. Bxe7 Qxe4 26. Rxe4 Bxe7 27. Rxe7
{ Black has saved his King for now, but ends up with a lost ending. Black capitulates within a couple more moves. }
27... Rxh4 28. f3 Rh8 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Master Games (Annotated)"]
[Black "Nakamura, Hikaru vs. Bareev, Evgeny"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2 f6 7. h4 Nd7 8. f4
{ The first departure from our theoretical section. f4 is a perfectly fine alternative, but I recommend h5 instead which keeps Black from trying to create counter-play with h5. }
8... Bf7 9. Be3
{ White plays for speed of development and has ready access to open the position up. }
9... h5
{ A logical attempt to create some counter-play, but Black currently has more pressing issues. He should likely either play fxe5 or Nh6 in an attempt to catch up in development. }
10. g5
{ This keeps the Rook on h8 out of play and creates more options to open the path to the King once he is fully prepared. }
10... Ne7 11. exf6
{ Taking immediately keeps the e-pawn vulnerable and begins opening lines against the King. }
11... gxf6 12. Ng3
{ Black getting a Knight to f5 is a major achievement in many lines. Ng3 gives Black a horrible light-square Bishop if he allow a Knight trade on f5. }
12... Qc7 13. Qf3
{ A very natural square for the Queen which defends the Knight and prepares for White to be able to castle long if desired. }
13... f5
{ Not a big fan of this move which makes the light-square Bishop bad for a long time. Black reasons this will close the position for some time and allow him to redirect the Knight to e4 via c8 and d6 when the Knight will be very strong and likely need to be traded off when one of the pawns will recapture and reopen the light-square Bishop. Personally, I prefer just castling long and leaving the tension between the f and g-pawn. }
14. O-O-O Bg6
{ Black should proceed immediately with the plan of routing a Knight to e4. Nc8 was probably better here. }
15. Kb1
{ White's most logical way in is to play for a c4 pawn break. Therefore, he should tuck his King to the side first for safety. }
15... Nc8 16. Nce2
{ White intends to improve the Knight by routing to e5 and clears the way for a c4 break at the same time. }
16... Nd6 17. Nc1 Ne4 18. c4
{ Nd3 makes sense, but White should likely play his break immediately while he can before Nb6 is played and helps Black make use of another piece that is currently poorly placed. }
18... O-O-O { Nb6 would offer more resistance. } 19. cxd5 { Opening lines. }
19... exd5 20. Nd3 Bg7 21. Bh3
{ An excellent move to tie down the Knight on d7 and therefore pressure the Knight on e4. If Black moves the Knight now, tactics involving Nxe4 with the f-pawn pinned become possible. }
21... Rdf8 22. Ka1
{ Ne5 immediately is stronger, but White elects to secure his King further and he retains a significant advantage at this point. }
22... Kb8 { Ending tactics based on captures on e4 if the Knight on d7 moves. }
23. Rhf1
{ White tries to add more pressure and/or restrain the f-pawn in the event he decides to recapture with the f-pawn if Black takes his Knight when it drops into e5. }
23... Ka8
{ An unnecessary loss of time. Black needed to add more protection to the f5 with Qc8 or seek counter-play with Qa5. }
24. Ne5 Nxe5 25. fxe5
{ The protected passed pawn is a winning positional advantage. } 25... Rf7
{ Seeking counter-play with c5 or reducing the material that White has to work with by Nxg3 was necessary. }
26. Bf4
{ Ne2 was much stronger when the threat of playing Nf4 gives Black serious problems to solve. }
26... Nxg3 27. Qxg3 Qe7 28. Rfe1 Qe6 29. Rc1
{ White has a decisive positional advantage, but the weak f-pawn is not enough alone. White needs to create a second weakness. Switching play to the queenside if the most natural way to seek that weakness. }
29... a6 30. Rc3 Rc8 31. Rec1 Bf8 32. Bf1 Rfc7 33. Be3 Bb4 34. R3c2
{ Tactically flawed due to the move played by Black. Rb3 was much stronger. }
34... f4 35. Bxf4 c5
{ A bizarre oversight when Bxc2 is practically decisive. One can only assume time pressure was coming into play given the break down in the quality of play from both sides. The rest of the game is given for continuity, but the quality is so poor it is not worth commentary. }
36. Bh3 Bxc2 37. Rxc2 Qg6 38. Rc1 cxd4 39. Bxc8 Rxc1+ 40. Bxc1 Qc2 41. Qg1 Qxc8
42. g6 Bf8 43. e6 d3 44. e7 Bxe7 45. g7 Qg8 46. Qd4 Qf7 47. a3 Bxh4 48. Be3 Kb8
49. Qf4+ *

