1. Nb5 Nec6 2. Nxg6
{ Correct on principle alone of doubling the Black g-pawns virtually any chance we get. However, also notable is that after   10...fxg6  11.Qd3  Kf7  12.gxh5  Rxh5  13.Bh3  Black cannot withstand the threat of  Bxe6+  followed by  Qxg6+  winning the Rook. Therefore, Black has to play  11...Kd7  with a significant advantage persisting for White. }
*

